The decision was part of the agreements reached at the end of a three day regional ministerial meeting held in Nigeria's capital Abuja. Herdsmen and farmers fights have remained the most predominately resource-use conflict in North-eastern Nigeria.

Last month, at least 16 people, mostly women and children, were killed in clashes between youths and cattle herders in central Nigeria. The violence in the village of Omutu, in the Okpokwu area of Benue state, is the latest flare-up linked to tensions over land and grazing rights in the restive region.

